<div class="comment-text">
<p>Is it then just limited to a “conservative” vs. “liberal” dichotomy? Why should not universities then increase the number of persons with lots of different viewpoints? Should we ensure that there are different intepretations of what caused the fall of the Ottoman Empire, for example? I don’t think that “increasing the number of conservatives” in history is a worthy of even plausable goal. History suffers most from an inability to be economically relevant and robust tools that can falsify claims. What is going to be done? Will more conservatives be “recruited” to major in history? Will historians have to teach from perspectives they don’t understand/believe in? The problem lies within the nature of the discipline, not the people in the discipline.</p>
